      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Mesh convergence and discretization error validation",
      "description": "Grid convergence index (GCI) study across three systematically refined meshes (4.2M, 12.1M, 31.7M cells). GCI for hemolysis index < 2.3% on fine mesh. Richardson extrapolation confirms asymptotic convergence. Discretization error within acceptable bounds for MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/validation/vr-02-experimental-comparison",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Experimental hemolysis comparison against FDA benchmark data",
      "description": "CFD-predicted normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) compared against published FDA generic centrifugal pump experimental data at 5 operating points (2500–3500 RPM, 3–7 L/min). Mean absolute error 8.4%; all predictions within experimental uncertainty bands. RH < 1 criterion satisfied at all worst-case operating points."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/validation/vr-03-uq-campaign",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Uncertainty quantification campaign — operating envelope sensitivity",
      "description": "A Latin hypercube sampling UQ campaign (n=128 samples) was executed across the 5-dimensional operating envelope (flow rate, rotational speed, blood viscosity, hematocrit, temperature). Sobol sensitivity indices were computed for all input parameters against the hemolysis QoI. Results documented in Morrison UQ Report v2.1 (internal ref: UQR-CPB-2024-002). The campaign confirmed that rotational speed and flow rate account for 87% of total output variance. All 128 sample predictions satisfied RH < 1. Sensitivity findings informed the factor assessments for Model Inputs and Model Form. Full structured linkage to the sensitivity analysis object is captured in the UQ report appendix."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/validation/vr-04-code-verification",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Numerical code verification — manufactured solutions",
      "description": "Method of manufactured solutions (MMS) applied to the SST k-omega turbulence model implementation. Order-of-accuracy confirmed at 1.97 (expected 2.0). No systematic coding errors identified. ANSYS Fluent 2023R1 software quality documentation reviewed and accepted."
