      "rationale": "Three-level mesh refinement study (4.2M, 12.1M, 31.7M cells) performed. GCI on fine mesh = 2.3% for NIH. Richardson extrapolation confirms monotonic convergence with refinement ratio 1.38. Exceeds MRL 2 requirement; production mesh selected at 12.1M cells balancing accuracy and computational cost."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions (flow rate, RPM, fluid properties) documented with uncertainty characterization and traceable to calibrated instrumentation.",
      "rationale": "FDA benchmark experimental data includes full documentation of test conditions: flow rates measured with Coriolis flowmeter (±0.5%), RPM with optical encoder (±10 RPM), blood analog viscosity with cone-plate rheometer (±3%). Test conditions are representative of clinical CPB operating range and adequately documented for MRL 2 comparison."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (MAE, RMSE, or equivalent) computed for NIH predictions versus experimental data; all predictions within experimental uncertainty bands at worst-case operating points.",
      "rationale": "NIH predicted at 5 operating points compared against FDA benchmark measurements. MAE = 8.4%, RMSE = 9.1%. All CFD predictions fall within ±2 standard deviations of experimental measurements. RH < 1 criterion satisfied at all operating points including worst-case condition (3500 RPM, 3 L/min). Output comparison requirement met."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoI (NIH and RH) directly maps to the clinical decision criterion and is computed from model outputs without additional unvalidated transformations.",
      "rationale": "The primary QoI is the normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) and relative hemolysis index (RH). Both quantities are directly computed from CFD velocity and shear stress fields using the Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law model. NIH is the standard regulatory metric for blood pump hemolysis assessment and directly supports the RH < 1 acceptance criterion. QoI relevance requirement met."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation geometry, fluid properties, and operating conditions are sufficiently similar to the COU device and operating envelope to support extrapolation of credibility findings.",
      "rationale": "Validation performed on FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry, which shares key hydraulic features (impeller diameter range, volute geometry, operating RPM) with the subject CPB device. Blood analog fluid (glycerol-water) properties matched to clinical hematocrit range. Operating conditions span the clinical CPB envelope (2.5–7 L/min, 2000–4000 RPM). Validation activities are sufficiently representative of the COU for MRL 2."
    },
